{"id":14880745,"mediaExerciseId":"42f8f4fd-ab7d-46ca-8331-803c59b17f4c","exerciseName":"6","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5899676,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to decide whether a negative operating cash flow is a good or bad sign for a particular period.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"It's not actually a bad sign for a company to have a negative operating cash flow for a particular period. This may indicate that the company spent more cash than it received. \n\nHowever, in reality, the company does not always make a profit every month. Some of them lose money and encourage negative cash flow in order to generate higher profits in the future.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/a05d220fcf5a5843d2efbe1992f4646c/b7abd2a82d04f8857c17fc811a46b82e/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/a05d220fcf5a5843d2efbe1992f4646c/b7abd2a82d04f8857c17fc811a46b82e/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"416653f0-fa0f-44e2-a5d4-adeb9cb121d8","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2},{"id":5977226,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"For this exercise, we will explain whether negative cash flows from assets indicate a good or bad sign for an entity.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Cash flows from assets pertain to all cash received from the usage of assets and paid for the acquisition of additional resources. It has three components, namely:\n\n1. Operating cash flows.\n2. Capital spending.\n3. Changes in net working capital.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The formula used to calculate cash flows from assets is as follows:\n\n$$\\begin {array}{lrr}\n\\text{Operating cash flows}&&\\$\\hspace{15pt}\\text{xx}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Net capital spending}&&\\text{xx}\\\\\n\\text{Less: Changes in NWC}&&\\underline{\\hspace{20pt}\\text{xx}}\\\\\n\\text{Depreciation expense}&&\\underline{\\underline{\\$\\hspace{10pt}\\text{XX}}}\\\\\n\\end{array}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/1ed2a710300c50aea4c6355be45d1a62/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":33,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/1ed2a710300c50aea4c6355be45d1a62/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"If an entity has positive cash flows from assets, it indicates that the entity **pays more for its creditors and business owners**. These amounts are funds available to settle liabilities or declare dividend payments to shareholders. Positive cash from operating assets is desirable because it would mean that the entity could generate more money for its business.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":145,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/584ed5ec6f21c4f7f24d0e5e5c747621/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":73,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/584ed5ec6f21c4f7f24d0e5e5c747621/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"On the other hand, negative cash flows from assets **do not explicitly says** that the business is not doing well. It only implies that an entity could raise more funds from debt and equity financing. For instance, the cash received from new borrowings and share subscriptions is greater than those paid for interests and dividends.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/d0561162d08ea91ca6e5bf38e1e97e1c/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":71,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/d0561162d08ea91ca6e5bf38e1e97e1c/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Whether cash flows from assets are positive or negative, it does not **directly reflect** business performance. Cash receipts and disbursements are not tantamount to revenues and expenses. Entities must properly manage cash by efficiently spending funds while maximizing total earnings.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":213,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/305123fbe55b40d29b38d9246fae8169/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":108,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/02/dc60d81cf167e3ce0539eac244c7c5d9/305123fbe55b40d29b38d9246fae8169/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"a09c4bd5-571d-4ee5-a575-09721797106f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880746,"exerciseName":"7","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"7ead2354-2ca0-4d31-a53d-4d50284a3fb2","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-7-7ead2354-2ca0-4d31-a53d-4d50284a3fb2"},{"id":14880747,"exerciseName":"8","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"78c9e296-8cf1-4bb6-8cc7-2206d12338a1","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-8-78c9e296-8cf1-4bb6-8cc7-2206d12338a1"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880744,"exerciseName":"5","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"81a4bd65-9de3-4544-8568-bbed3057293d","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-5-81a4bd65-9de3-4544-8568-bbed3057293d"},{"id":14880743,"exerciseName":"4","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a2a2189f-6fee-4411-8f79-b9a0e5dd5c93","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-4-a2a2189f-6fee-4411-8f79-b9a0e5dd5c93"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-6-42f8f4fd-ab7d-46ca-8331-803c59b17f4c"}